This paper proposes the existence and explicit derivation of a novel class of "Propagator-Stabilizing Transformations" (PSTs) for the Horndeski Lagrangian. These PSTs are a specific type of coupled, non-linear transformation involving both the metric $g_{\mu\nu}$ and the scalar field $\phi$, extending the concept of disformal invariance by incorporating field-dependent shifts in $\phi$. The groundbreaking aspect lies in demonstrating that invariance under these PSTs uniquely constrains the Horndeski functions $G_i(\phi, X)$ to a "protected sector" of theories that are demonstrably free from ghosts and tachyons at tree-level and, crucially, at the one-loop perturbative level in an FRW background. The analysis will explicitly show the transformation rules for $g_{\mu\nu}$ and $\phi$, explain how Galilean symmetry emerges as a special case of these PSTs, and investigate their compatibility with observational constraints on gravitational wave speed, cosmological expansion, and structure growth. Furthermore, the work will argue that these PSTs represent the "certain symmetries" discussed in Ref. 2004.11655, preventing the reappearance of ghosts at higher loop orders.
