This paper proposes the existence and explicit derivation of a novel "Generalized Disformal-Shift Symmetry" (DSS) for the Horndeski Lagrangian. These DSS transformations, acting on both the metric $g_{\mu\nu}$ and the scalar field $\phi$, are shown to uniquely constrain the Horndeski functions $G_i(\phi, X)$ to a "quantum-protected sub-sector." The groundbreaking aspect lies in demonstrating that invariance under these DSS transformations inherently guarantees freedom from ghosts at tree-level and, critically, *prevents their generation at the one-loop perturbative level* in an FRW background, aligning with the arguments of Ref. 2004.11655. The analysis will explicitly provide the DSS transformation rules, explain how Galilean symmetry emerges as a special case, and thoroughly assess the compatibility of this protected sub-sector with observational constraints on gravitational wave speed, cosmological expansion, and structure growth. This approach bypasses the monumental task of full one-loop effective action calculation by showing how the DSS directly constrains the quantum kinetic terms to remain positive.
